CAPE TOWN &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan said on Thursday Treasury has spoken to ratings agencies S&amp;P, Fitch and Moody&#8217;s after delivering a budget that targeted the wealthy with tax hikes in a bid to rein in the budget deficit.Responding to a comment from a member of a parliamentary committee that ratings firms were infringing on the country s sovereignty, Gordhan defended the need for South Africa to deal with the agencies.&#8220;We don&#8217;t allow them to govern South Africa &#8230; We have political and fiscal sovereignty,&#8221; Gordhan said.